-- ── Burnermail ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Burner Mail (burnermail.io) is a privacy-focused browser extension and email-forwarding service that generates disposable, anonymous email addresses (burners) on demand so users never have to hand their real inbox to unfamiliar websites, newsletters, or online forms. Once installed, its extension detects email input fields and instantly creates a unique burner address that forwards messages straight to the user's real inbox, letting them reply from that burner identity without ever exposing their true address to the sender. If a particular burner starts attracting spam or gets sold to third parties, users can disable that single address without affecting any other account tied to their real email, effectively creating an unlimited set of throwaway identities that can each be individually revoked. Burner Mail says it is trusted by more than 373,000 users and has been covered by outlets including Lifehacker, Wired, and Digital Trends. The company has scaled back or removed parts of its free tier over time, pushing most functionality behind a paid Premium subscription that also unlocks features like connecting a custom domain and routing a single burner to multiple real inboxes for shared or team use, making it best suited to privacy-conscious individuals and small teams rather than large organizations.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / subscription (a legacy free tier exists but is being scaled back; full pricing is confirmed at signup rather than published in detail)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Premium subscription, commonly cited around $29.99 per year in third-party listings - confirm current pricing directly on burnermail.io before purchase$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small / indie team (exact headcount not publicly disclosed)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Burner Mail Review: Disposable Email Addresses for Privacy$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Burner Mail generates disposable burner email addresses that forward to your real inbox. See how it works, its features, and what Premium costs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Burner Mail, available at burnermail.io, is an email-privacy service built around the idea of disposable, single-use email addresses that shield a user's real inbox from spam, tracking, and data breaches. Rather than requiring people to manually create and manage separate email accounts, Burner Mail provides a browser extension that recognizes email input fields on websites and automatically generates a unique, randomly named burner address on the spot. Every message sent to that burner is transparently forwarded to the user's real inbox, so day-to-day communication is not disrupted, while the recipient's actual email address remains hidden from whatever site, newsletter, or service the burner was created for. Users can reply to incoming messages directly from the burner identity, preserving anonymity in both directions, and each burner can be individually disabled if it starts attracting spam or is discovered to have been sold or leaked to a third party - critically, disabling one burner has no effect on any other account, so a single bad actor cannot compromise a user's entire email footprint. Burner Mail markets itself as having a large, established user base, citing more than 373,100 users, and highlights media coverage from outlets such as Lifehacker, Wired, Zapier's blog, Digital Trends, and Product Hunt as evidence of its longevity and reputation in the disposable-email space. Its Premium tier adds capabilities aimed at more advanced or team-oriented use, including the ability to connect a custom domain so burner addresses look more professional (for example, name@yourdomain.com), and the option to forward a single burner address to multiple real recipients, which is useful for shared family accounts or small teams managing a common inbox. On the transparency side, Burner Mail's public marketing pages do not spell out a detailed pricing table; the company's own FAQ states plainly that the service cannot remain free indefinitely because it has real running costs and a team behind it, and third-party software directories note that specific pricing is often only revealed during signup or checkout, with some aggregator listings citing a Premium price near $29.99 per year, though that figure should be verified directly on the official site since it can change and may vary by promotion. Independent reviews on platforms like Capterra give Burner Mail a solid but not exceptional reputation, with an average rating around 4 out of 5 stars; some reviewers note that its pricing is higher than certain competing disposable-email tools, or that they eventually switched to alternatives offering more features for less money. There is also no publicly available information about Burner Mail's founding date, founding team, or company headquarters, which is common for smaller, privacy-oriented consumer software companies that intentionally keep a low corporate profile. Overall, Burner Mail is positioned less as an enterprise security product and more as a consumer-grade privacy tool: a lightweight, browser-extension-driven way for individuals, freelancers, and small teams to reduce spam, limit tracking, and regain control over who has access to their real email address, at the cost of a recurring subscription once the free tier's limits are exhausted.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '892b9c2b-f173-4064-afce-b923fcc25209';

