-- ── Cabot ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cabot is a free, open-source, self-hosted monitoring and alerting platform originally built as an internal Christmas project at Arachnys, a London-based data and research technology company, before being open-sourced under the MIT license around 2014. Positioned as a lightweight, self-hosted alternative to commercial tools like PagerDuty, Server Density, Pingdom, and Nagios, Cabot lets teams watch Graphite/StatsD metrics, Jenkins build jobs, and HTTP endpoints for problems, group related checks into logical services and instance dashboards, and page on-call staff by phone, SMS, HipChat, or email when something breaks. Built with Python and Django, Cabot was designed to be deployable in minutes using Docker, and it exposes a REST API with authentication so checks and alerts can be managed programmatically. However, the project's own GitHub repository carries a prominent notice that Cabot is stable and used in production by hundreds of companies and individuals, but is no longer actively maintained by Arachnys, which has been looking to hand the project to new maintainers; its most recent tagged release, 0.11.7, shipped in September 2017. That makes Cabot best understood today as a mature, historically well-regarded piece of self-hosted monitoring infrastructure that still works for teams willing to run and patch it themselves, rather than an actively evolving product with ongoing vendor support.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open source (self-hosted)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Originally built by Arachnys; now an unmaintained/community-status open-source project with no dedicated company behind it$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$N/A - open-source project (originally built by Arachnys, London, UK)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cabot Review: Self-Hosted Monitoring and Alerting (Status 2026)$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cabot is a free, open-source, self-hosted monitoring and alerting tool from Arachnys. See its features, architecture, and current maintenance status.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cabot is an open-source, self-hosted infrastructure monitoring and alerting platform that was originally created inside Arachnys, a London-based technology company known for data extraction and research automation tools, as what the project's own documentation describes as a Christmas side project. Rather than keeping it internal, Arachnys chose to open-source Cabot, releasing it under the permissive MIT license, with public activity on its GitHub repository and issue tracker visible from around 2014 onward, which is generally treated as the point at which the project became a usable, community-facing tool rather than an internal experiment. Cabot's design goal was to give engineering teams many of the practical benefits of commercial monitoring and paging services - specifically drawing comparisons to PagerDuty, Server Density, Pingdom, and Nagios - without their licensing costs or operational complexity, by being simple enough to deploy in a matter of minutes, particularly via Docker. Functionally, Cabot is built to plug into monitoring data teams likely already have rather than requiring a brand-new collection agent stack: it can watch metrics already being sent to Graphite or StatsD, monitor the status of Jenkins build and deployment jobs, and perform HTTP endpoint checks to catch web service outages. Checks can be grouped logically into services and physically into instance-level dashboards, mirroring how real infrastructure is typically organized, and when something fails, Cabot can notify on-call staff through multiple channels including phone calls, SMS text messages, HipChat, and email. Under the hood, Cabot is a Python application built on the Django web framework, with a REST API that supports authentication and permission controls, allowing checks, services, and alert configurations to be managed programmatically rather than only through its web interface. This combination made Cabot a popular, pragmatic choice for engineering teams in the mid-2010s who wanted PagerDuty-style alerting without paying for a hosted SaaS product or building an in-house paging system from scratch. However, prospective adopters in 2026 need to weigh a significant caveat that Arachnys itself has posted prominently on the project's GitHub page: Cabot is described as stable and still used in production by hundreds of companies and individuals, but it is explicitly not actively maintained, and Arachnys has stated it would like to hand the project off to new, responsible maintainers rather than continuing to drive development itself. Consistent with that notice, the project's most recent tagged release, version 0.11.7, was published in September 2017, and the codebase has seen limited meaningful activity since. This means integrations tied to services that have changed significantly or shut down since 2017 - HipChat itself, for example, was discontinued by Atlassian in 2019 - are likely to be stale or broken without manual patching by whoever deploys Cabot. In practical terms, Cabot today should be evaluated as a mature but effectively frozen piece of open-source infrastructure: technically capable and battle-tested for its era, free to self-host with no licensing cost, and still functional for teams willing to maintain, patch, and possibly fork it themselves, but not a product with an active vendor, a current roadmap, or guaranteed security patching going forward.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1edb450a-0531-4854-a16b-c23fd485bcce';

