-- ── Cacheflow ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cacheflow was a modern B2B quote-to-cash software company - not related to the 1990s/2000s 'CacheFlow' web-caching appliance maker that was later renamed Blue Coat Systems. This Cacheflow was founded in 2021 by Brian Zotter and Sarika Garg and based in Los Altos, California, building a no-code CPQ (configure-price-quote), billing, and subscription-management platform aimed at helping SaaS sales teams close and renew deals faster. Its product let sales reps generate quotes, offer usage-based pricing, multi-year ramps, and buy-now-pay-later financing, and hand buyers a self-serve, white-labeled checkout that Cacheflow marketed as closing deals in as few as eight clicks. The company raised roughly 16 million dollars in seed funding from investors including GV (Google Ventures) and GGV Capital. In October 2024, Cacheflow was acquired by HubSpot, and its quote-to-cash capabilities have since been folded into HubSpot's Commerce Hub and Revenue Hub product lines, where CPQ, billing, and payments now live as native HubSpot features rather than a standalone Cacheflow product; Cacheflow's own marketing site now redirects visitors to HubSpot's CPQ page. Prospective buyers researching Cacheflow today are effectively evaluating HubSpot's CPQ/Revenue Hub offering, which requires a Revenue Hub Professional or Enterprise seat rather than a separate Cacheflow subscription.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Formerly subscription/seat-based SaaS; now bundled into HubSpot Revenue Hub (Professional/Enterprise) pricing rather than sold standalone$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Not sold standalone; included within HubSpot Revenue Hub plans (contact HubSpot for current pricing)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Formerly a venture-backed startup (around 16 million dollars raised); now operated as part of HubSpot, a large public company$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Formerly Los Altos, California, USA; now operated as part of HubSpot (Cambridge, Massachusetts)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cacheflow Review: The Quote-to-Cash Startup Acquired by HubSpot$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cacheflow was a no-code CPQ and billing platform for SaaS sales teams, acquired by HubSpot in 2024. See what it did and where its technology lives now.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cacheflow is the name of a modern, venture-backed B2B software company that built a quote-to-cash platform for SaaS sales teams - and it is important to distinguish it clearly from an unrelated, much older company: the original 'CacheFlow, Inc.' was a web-caching appliance vendor from the late 1990s and early 2000s that later renamed itself Blue Coat Systems, a company with no connection to this modern Cacheflow beyond a similar-sounding name. The Cacheflow relevant here was founded in 2021 by Brian Zotter and Sarika Garg and was headquartered in Los Altos, California. Its core product addressed a well-known pain point in SaaS sales: the slow, manual, spreadsheet-and-DocuSign-driven process of turning a sales conversation into a signed, paid contract, commonly referred to in the industry as quote-to-cash. Cacheflow's platform offered no-code CPQ (configure, price, quote) tooling that let sales reps quickly assemble accurate quotes without engineering or RevOps involvement, combined with support for more sophisticated modern pricing models such as usage-based billing, multi-year pricing ramps, and buy-now-pay-later-style financing options that are increasingly common in enterprise SaaS deals. A signature part of its pitch was a self-serve, white-labeled checkout experience for buyers, which Cacheflow marketed as being able to close deals in as few as eight clicks, reducing friction on the buyer's side of the transaction in addition to speeding up the seller's quoting process. On the business side, Cacheflow raised approximately 16 million dollars in total seed-stage venture funding across two rounds, with backing from high-profile investors including GV (Google's venture capital arm) and GGV Capital, signaling strong early confidence in the team and the quote-to-cash market opportunity. In September 2022, the company publicly announced the launch of zero-code, usage-based pricing and billing capabilities aimed at accelerating SaaS sales further, reflecting the industry-wide shift toward consumption-based and hybrid pricing models during that period. The company's trajectory changed significantly in October 2024, when it was acquired by HubSpot, the large, publicly traded CRM and marketing platform. Rather than continuing to operate and market Cacheflow as an independent, standalone product, HubSpot has folded its CPQ, billing, and quote-to-cash capabilities into its own Commerce Hub and Revenue Hub product lines; as confirmation of this, Cacheflow's marketing website (getcacheflow.com) now redirects visitors directly to HubSpot's CPQ product page. Functionally, this means the technology and team that built Cacheflow now live inside HubSpot's broader CRM and revenue-management ecosystem, with CPQ, billing, and payments available as native features to customers on HubSpot's Revenue Hub Professional or Enterprise tiers, rather than as a separate purchase. For anyone researching Cacheflow today, the practical takeaway is that the standalone product and independent company effectively no longer exist in the market; what remains is the underlying quote-to-cash technology, now integrated into and sold as part of HubSpot's platform, which also means prospective buyers should evaluate HubSpot's overall CRM and Revenue Hub ecosystem and pricing rather than expecting to purchase Cacheflow as a discrete point solution.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '568eb44d-bbd9-4755-b8c8-7b71d8e9489d';

