-- ── CacheFly ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CacheFly is a long-running, privately held content delivery network (CDN) provider that traces its roots to Downloadhosting.com, a file-distribution service for small software developers founded by CTO Matt Levine in 1999; the company launched its CacheFly CDN brand and pioneered TCP Anycast-based content delivery between 2002 and 2005, making it one of the earliest Anycast CDNs in the industry. Now headquartered in the Chicago, Illinois area (with a fully remote team of roughly two dozen employees spread across North America, Europe, and South America), CacheFly positions itself as a premium, boutique alternative to hyperscale CDNs for customers - particularly in media and entertainment, gaming, and ad tech - who need fast, reliable, highly controllable content delivery rather than the lowest possible price. Its network spans more than 75 points of presence across all seven continents, and its proprietary BestHop routing technology automatically selects the fastest path between a customer's origin server and end users. Recent product investments include Advanced Analytics, an EdgeControl JavaScript engine for programmable edge logic, and Terraform integration for infrastructure-as-code CDN management, showcased at NAB Show 2026. Pricing is transparently published, ranging from a free developer tier through usage-based Business and Enterprise tiers to custom, quote-based High Volume plans for petabyte-scale customers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Usage-based tiered pricing, published on the company's website, with custom quotes for enterprise and high-volume customers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free developer tier (up to 100 GB); paid Business plans start around $300 per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2002, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small, private company - approximately 26 employees, fully remote across North America, Europe, and South America$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Chicago area (Elk Grove Village, Illinois), USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CacheFly Review: Pricing, Network and Features of This CDN$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CacheFly is a premium private CDN founded in 2002. See its Anycast network, BestHop routing, pricing tiers, and who it's best suited for in 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CacheFly is a content delivery network (CDN) provider with one of the longer operating histories in its industry, and its origin story predates the CacheFly brand itself. The company traces back to Downloadhosting.com, a file-distribution service launched in 1999 by CTO Matt Levine to help small software developers distribute their products online. Building on that early infrastructure, the company launched the CacheFly CDN service and, between 2002 and 2005, became one of the first providers to pioneer TCP Anycast-based content delivery, a routing technique that lets a single IP address be announced from many locations so that user requests are automatically directed to the nearest or best-performing point of presence - a technology approach that many later CDNs would go on to adopt as an industry standard. Today CacheFly is a privately held company headquartered in the Chicago, Illinois area, more specifically associated with an address in Elk Grove Village, Illinois, and it operates with a fully remote team of roughly 26 employees spread across North America, Europe, and South America as of recent reporting. Being privately held allows the company to make long-term decisions for customers and staff without the pressure of quarterly public-market performance, a point CacheFly itself emphasizes in its marketing. Rather than competing primarily on being the largest possible network, CacheFly positions itself as a premium, boutique CDN built for customers who need tightly controlled performance and reliability, especially in media and entertainment (particularly video-on-demand and live streaming), gaming (patch and asset delivery), and ad-tech (real-time content and bidding infrastructure) - sectors where delivery speed and consistency have a direct impact on revenue. Its network spans more than 75 points of presence across all seven continents, and its proprietary BestHop technology continuously evaluates routing paths to automatically select the fastest, most reliable hop between a customer's origin infrastructure and end users, aiming to optimize performance dynamically rather than relying on static routing rules. The company has continued to invest in modern CDN tooling: recent product developments highlighted at NAB Show 2026, a major broadcast and media technology conference, include Advanced Analytics for deeper traffic and performance visibility, an EdgeControl JavaScript engine that lets customers write and run custom logic at the network edge, and Terraform integration that allows CDN configuration to be managed through infrastructure-as-code workflows, appealing to engineering teams that want CDN management to fit into modern DevOps practices. On pricing, CacheFly differentiates itself from many CDN competitors by publishing a relatively transparent tiered structure rather than requiring a sales conversation for every customer: a free Developer tier includes up to 100 GB of usage per month with a per-gigabyte overage charge and support for one domain; a Business tier starts around 300 dollars per month for a 10 terabyte allotment, scaling up through higher data tiers with lower per-gigabyte overage rates and more domains and support channels included; an Enterprise tier starts around 2,000 dollars per month at the 100 terabyte level, with further tiers up to 500 terabytes and priority support including a dedicated Slack channel; and a High Volume tier offers custom, quote-based pricing for petabyte-scale customers who need private CDN nodes, additional security tooling, and white-glove implementation support. Overall, CacheFly's combination of a long operating history, a genuinely global Anycast network, published pricing, and a deliberately smaller, high-touch support model makes it a fit for media, gaming, and ad-tech companies that prioritize performance and personal support over simply choosing the biggest-name hyperscale CDN, while its smaller global footprint and team size relative to giants like Cloudflare, Akamai, or Fastly are tradeoffs worth weighing for customers with extremely large or highly diversified delivery requirements.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f46c4b38-6951-443a-af17-7bf78dbe3b27';

